    <item>
      <title>Re: Magician or Rogue?</title>
      <link>http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq/board/message?board.id=Progression&amp;message.id=18732#M18732</link>
      <description>A mage rocks a rogue during classic.&amp;nbsp; After that I'd say they are about&#xD;
equal in a group the rest of the way.&amp;nbsp; A rogue with good gear may do&#xD;
more pure DPS than a mage, but a mage also brings things like stuns&#xD;
from their pet, damage shields, mod rods, and the ability to do spike&#xD;
DPS when needed.&amp;nbsp; Keep in mind, epics are very important items for both&#xD;
the rogue and mage to be very effective, and the rogue epic is MUCH&#xD;
easier, but once a mage gets their epic they dominate against Kunark /&#xD;
Velious era XP mobs (the pet can off tank as well as a warrior, and it&#xD;
also out aggros pretty much everything (due to its DD proc that procs&#xD;
at an insane rate, and its stun), so it can be used to get mobs off&#xD;
clerics and enchanters who over aggro; before pets were changed to not&#xD;
hold aggro if any PC was also in melee range (thanks Legacy of Steel&#xD;
;D), the epic would often pull aggro from a warrior, and could be used&#xD;
as the groups MT in some situations).&amp;nbsp; Once a rogue gets Primal things&#xD;
even out again.&amp;nbsp; &lt;br&gt;&#xD;
&lt;br&gt;&#xD;
Rogues are much more equipment dependent than mages, so if you aren't&#xD;
going to play enough to be in a high end raiding guild, you may feel&#xD;
mre powerful as a mage.&amp;nbsp; On the other hand, a rogue decked out in the&#xD;
latest raiding gear will always be a monster damage dealing machine.&amp;nbsp;&#xD;
Also, pets lose more effectiveness against higher level NPCs than PCs&#xD;
do (due to the level gap between pets and the mobs), so when crawling&#xD;
through a tough single group dungeon, such as SG or Velketor's castle,&#xD;
a mages DPS will drop more in relation to the rogues.&lt;br&gt;&#xD;
&lt;br&gt;&#xD;
On raids, rogues are generally in higher demand than mages.&amp;nbsp; Having one&#xD;
or two mages is more important than having a rogue in most cases (until&#xD;
traps in luclin), due to CoH, damage sheilds, malosini (its a lot nicer&#xD;
to have mages for malosini, so Shamams can go straight to attempting&#xD;
slow after Malo/Tash is on), and mod rods (not too important until&#xD;
Luclin introduces Mod Rod 2s), but after the necessities are taken care&#xD;
of, adding rogues is much better than adding more mages.&amp;nbsp; Pet damage is&#xD;
crippled against raid mobs, and in many cases are raped by AEs, or&#xD;
simply can't be used.&amp;nbsp; On top of that, mage nukes are often resisted or&#xD;
partially resisted against boss mobs, and require melee range in order&#xD;
to have a chance of doing damage.&amp;nbsp; This is only true until Luclin&#xD;
though.&amp;nbsp; Bolt spells are also nearly impossible to hit a mob with on a&#xD;
raid unless you levitate.&amp;nbsp; &lt;br&gt;&#xD;
&lt;br&gt;&#xD;
Raiding as a mage is frustrating until Luclin, but honestly, playing a&#xD;
more useful raiding class doesn't make the raids that much better.&amp;nbsp;&#xD;
Raiding satisfaction comes from the performance of the guild as a&#xD;
whole, rather than knowing you did more damage than guildmate Y.&amp;nbsp; I&#xD;
should add that you may find raiding as a mage less repetitive and/or&#xD;
boring.&amp;nbsp; As a rogue your entire raiding career will be /assist, auto&#xD;
attack, BS, BS, evade, etc., with the occasional scouting request, up&#xD;
until Luclin when you are needed to disarm traps.&amp;nbsp; As a mage, in&#xD;
addition to sending your pet in and casting nukes, you will also be&#xD;
apart of the debuff/slow team, have to make sure the tanks always have&#xD;
a DS on, setup CoH for latecomers, and spit out mod rods when needed.&lt;br&gt;&#xD;
&lt;br&gt;&#xD;
I'd say it comes down to what style of play you prefer.&amp;nbsp; Would you rather be a caster or a melee?&lt;br&gt;&#xD;
&lt;br&gt;&#xD;
PS: back it the day a lot of people underestimated the usefulness of a&#xD;
mage in an XP group.&amp;nbsp; At one time there were legitimate reasons behind&#xD;
this belief: pets used to be much harder to control, and a lot of mages&#xD;
did not control their pets well.&amp;nbsp; Pets used to be on the same faction&#xD;
as the mage, so poor pathing could get the group trained if the mage&#xD;
wasn't paying attention.&amp;nbsp; Also, until partway through luclin, pets&#xD;
would not refuse to attack mezed mobs and would not automatically stop&#xD;
attacking a mob once it was mezed, so are careless mage was liable to&#xD;
break mezes and get enchanters killed.&amp;nbsp; Pets also used to take a&#xD;
significant amount of XP if they did more than of the NPCs HP in&#xD;
damage.&amp;nbsp; This was only ever an issue in classic, and in Kunark /&#xD;
Velious if the mage had an epic, but a lot of people still just assumed&#xD;
pet = less XP.&amp;nbsp; These are no longer issues today, but some players&#xD;
still may have a bias against mages when choosing people for XP&#xD;
groups.&amp;nbsp; Just a warning.&lt;br&gt;&#xD;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</description>
